00:01.300 --> 00:11.160
Okay, I guess the tape is rolling, so we might as well start. First of all, I
wondered how you became involved in science fiction when you were younger. Did

00:11.160 --> 00:21.160
you read it a lot when you were young? Yes, I started reading science fiction, I
suppose, about the earliest form of literature that I read. I never made a

00:21.160 --> 00:35.980
mental distinction between science fiction, fantasy, anything of that nature
because my parents brought it to me to read and I just simply regarded it as the

00:35.980 --> 00:46.560
most interesting reading material that I had accessible. So naturally, when I
began turning to writing, that's what I wrote.

00:51.640 --> 01:02.400
Why did you start writing science fiction? Well, actually, they took my
television program off the air. Our television, at that time, I was 10.

01:02.720 --> 01:12.420
Television hadn't been around in private homes very long. I had just time enough
to get thoroughly addicted to television science fiction, and then it ran its

01:12.420 --> 01:22.680
course, and it was gone from the air. So I, in a fit of mourning, went into the
bedroom, picked up a tablet and pencil, and started writing my own novels.

01:25.640 --> 01:37.760
Your first published novel, I think, was around 1976, The Gate of Ivrel? Yes,
yes. Had you published any stories before then? No, not for want of trying, but

01:37.760 --> 01:53.200
I've never regarded myself as a short story writer. I don't tend to think in
that convenient length. And consequently, I wrote novels and novels and novels

01:53.200 --> 02:08.880
and was actually turned in Brothers of Earth first. And since there seemed to be
some question about it being a little long, as many of my works tend to be. I

02:08.880 --> 02:19.880
very, very quickly wrote Gate of Ivrel while teaching school, et cetera, and
managed to get it finished inside two months.

02:23.500 --> 02:34.700
One thing I wondered is, you said that you didn't distinguish between science
fiction and the other reading that you did, but I wonder why you didn't do some

02:34.700 --> 02:43.500
other kind of writing instead of science fiction I think you could have been a
writer in almost any area that you tried I don't write the other things because

02:43.500 --> 02:57.580
I don't like them in general I find that I suppose the only thing outside of
science fiction that I've ever tried my hand at writing has been mysteries and I

02:57.580 --> 03:09.220
don't care for the modern fashion of those and I've always viewed them is a
great deal more fun to read than they are to write, mostly because you have to

03:09.220 --> 03:24.540
be extremely controlled, and I suspect that mystery writers have to know who did
it. And I'd rather not know the end of my books. The other thing that I've tried

03:24.540 --> 03:33.580
my hand at is historical fiction, and I find, again, that's a straight jacket
because you're rather well held with what happened, whether or not it makes

03:33.580 --> 03:40.220
artistic sense. So, just for the sheer pleasure of writing, I prefer science
fiction.

